From Midgaard's registry perspective, the Arroyo is archival evidence of what happens to a legal system when documentation infrastructure collapses: law persists as ritual, ritual decays into extortion, physical inscriptions remain as competing legitimacy claims no surviving authority can adjudicate. The palimpsest inscriptions — Keeper numerics under Ledger seals under Moon clauses — are the documentary equivalent of Midgaard's contested archive records: each regime rewrote prior authority in its own vocabulary without destroying the prior text. The Arroyo's Charter Reclaimers — carrying copied charter rods and counterfeit witness seals, claiming to "enforce ancient passage law" — are the endpoint of a sequence that begins when authentic institutional authority is not maintained and counterfeited authority fills the vacuum. Midgaard's Lantern Registry, Guard Command patrols, and Magistrate Ledgerhouse archive maintenance are mechanisms for keeping authentic institutional authority distinguishable from counterfeited claims. The Reckoning faction cites the Arroyo as evidence of what sealed archives become after institutional failure: palimpsest claims that every faction reads as legitimating their incompatible project.

