The Arroyo's multi-layer inscription archaeology is the physical version of the institutional problem Kiess's anti-sealed-warrant doctrine addresses. When Evermeet issued sealed warrants transferring condemned debtors to the Conclave, those warrants applied administrative vocabulary from one domain (arcane-material handling) to a category (persons) it was not designed to process. The Arroyo's Moon-descending legal language reframing debt default as spiritual trespass is the same mechanism: administrative categories imported from funerary jurisdiction applied to water debt, producing category contamination where debtors become candidates for sentence-binding. Kiess's founding charter clause — "no sealed warrant issued by a predecessor authority shall bind a Kiess citizen" — is a categorical barrier against this cross-domain classification contamination. The clause does not specify which predecessor authority or vocabulary; it prohibits the mechanism regardless.

