The Arroyo and the Saltglass Reach share institutional DNA: both transformed geographic features into jurisdictional boundaries, both attempted to reconcile incompatible legal traditions through procedural compromise, both saw legitimate passage-law vocabulary preserved in form while corrupted in practice. The Arroyo's Charter Reclaimers are functionally identical to the Saltglass Reach's competing toll claimants — the same legal vocabulary of passage authorization, the same practical function of extracting payment from travelers who cannot verify the authority's legitimacy. Some Arroyo "thirst oath" vocabulary appears in adapted form on Reach cairn tablets, suggesting the two regions were once part of the same legal-linguistic tradition. Mafdet's Shoreward Conversion — inland law and maritime law explicitly distinguished, with dual attestation required before cargo crosses the threshold — is the institutional response to the vocabulary contamination that destroyed the Arroyo's legal coherence: keeping frameworks separate rather than allowing administrative categories to bleed across the boundary.

