The Arroyo's "unpaid names" — dead travelers with funerary rites withheld pending debt settlement — are a specific spiritual crisis in Khenari terms. A person whose rites are withheld cannot complete the descent passage; their name remains active in a transitional state without the anchor of completed rites. The Salt Ledger era's practice of treating death as a ledger entry produced a category of unresolved names whose spiritual status is indeterminate. Whether these names can be retroactively resolved through later rite-completion is disputed: the Sepulchrists' "final lawful resonance" would, in Khenari terms, not resolve the unpaid names but impose a new administrative framework over them — trading one form of institutional incomplete-record for another. Genuine resolution would require identifying which names remain unresolved, tracing their descent chains, and providing missing rites through whatever institution still holds relevant jurisdiction. The Reed Ledger Wardens' practical-records tradition — maintaining surviving gauges and witness-lamp standards — is the closest surviving institution to what would be needed.

